<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="active-transport">Active Transport</h2><ul><li><p>Active transport is the <b>movement of molecules and ions through a cell membrane from a region of lower concentration to a region of higher concentration</b></p><ul><li><p>Active transport <b>requires energy</b> in the form of <b>ATP </b>from respiration to move substances <b>against their</b> <b>concentration gradient</b>; hence this is an <b>active </b>process</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Active transport requires <b>carrier proteins</b></p><ul><li><p>Each carrier protein is specific to a particular type of molecule or ion</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Energy is required to allow the carrier protein to<b> change shape</b>; this transfers the molecules or ions across the cell membrane</p><ul><li><p>The <b>energy required is provided by ATP </b>(adenosine triphosphate) produced during respiration</p></li><li><p>The ATP is <span class="popovers" data-content="The breaking down of large molecules into smaller ones by the addition of water molecules." data-title="Hydrolysis" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">hydrolysed</span> to release energy</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Carrier protein in active transport" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="565" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Carrier-protein-in-active-transport.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Active transport moves substances across a membrane from low to high concentration. Note that ATP is required for carrier proteins to change shape.</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Examples of active transport include</p><ul><li><p><b>Reabsorption</b> of useful molecules and ions <b>into the blood</b> after filtration into the kidney tubules</p></li><li><p><b>Absorption </b>of some products of digestion from the digestive tract<b> into the blood</b></p></li><li><p><b>Loading sugar</b> from the photosynthesising cells of leaves <b>into the phloem</b> tissue for transport around the plant</p></li><li><p><b>Loading inorganic ions</b> from the soil <b>into root hair cells</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="endocytosis">Endocytosis</h4><ul><li><p>Some molecules are <b>too large</b> to travel via membrane proteins, e.g.</p><ul><li><p>Proteins</p></li><li><p>Lipids</p></li><li><p>Some carbohydrates</p></li></ul></li><li><p>In such cases a cell can <b>surround a substance with a section of the cell surface membrane</b></p><ul><li><p>The membrane <b>engulfs</b> the substance and pinches off inside the cell to form a <b>temporary vacuole</b> with the ingested substance contained inside</p></li><li><p>This is <b>endocytosis</b></p><ul><li><p><span class="popovers" data-content="The mechanism by which phagocytes engulf particles to form a vesicle or a vacuole." data-title="Phagocytosis" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">Phagocytosis</span> is an example of endocytosis</p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>Endocytosis is an <b>active process </b>and requires a source of energy</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Phagocytosis of a bacterium" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="689" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/01/Phagocytosis-of-a-bacterium.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Phagocytosis is an example of endocytosis; the cell surface membrane extends around a pathogen, engulfing it and enclosing it within a temporary vacuole inside the cell</b></i></p><h4 id="exocytosis">Exocytosis</h4><ul><li><p>Some substances produced by the cell need to be <b>secreted</b>, such as hormones, some enzymes, and lipids</p></li><li><p><b>Vesicles</b> containing the substance <b>pinch off from sacs of the Golgi apparatus </b></p></li><li><p>These vesicles are moved toward the cell surface and fuse with the cell surface membrane to be released outside the cell</p><ul><li><p>This is <b>exocytosis</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Exocytosis is an <b>active process</b> and requires a source of energy</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="endocytosis-and-exocytosis" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="905" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="endocytosis-and-exocytosis.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/04/endocytosis-and-exocytosis.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/04/endocytosis-and-exocytosis.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/04/endocytosis-and-exocytosis.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/04/endocytosis-and-exocytosis.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,wi